II. PROPOSED METHOD
A. Overall Framework
MDFformer uses the AFFormer-base encoder [13] , pretrained on the ImageNet-1k, as its backbone. As shown in Fig. 1 (a), the process begins by embedding those into overlapping patch embeddings. These embeddings are then passed through a dual-stream encoder separately (four AFF-blocks, each processing both RGB and DSM features in parallel). The core of the fusion process is handled by two key modules: the CSFM and SDEM. After each block, the features are sent through a branch into the CSFM to shuffle and interact with multi-scale features. The output of CSFM not only returns to the main branch but also passes through an SDEM to further enhance features. Finally, the multi-scale outputs from multiple SDEM modules are fed into an FPN head decoder. Notably, the different scale feature maps fused by FPN during forward inference will generate their own additional loss.
During backpropagation, the gradient flows are influenced by both the total loss and the individual loss from each scale.
B. CSFM
The key to enhancing dense labeling accuracy lies in leveraging the complementary information. To achieve this, a novel module for cross-modal shuffling and fusion has been developed. The process begins by extracting features and concatenating them, and is followed by a series of operations that promote cross-modal interaction, as shown in Fig. 1 (b). Initially, R (RGB) and D (DSM) undergo channel concatenation. A Spatial MLP φ1 is then applied to extract cross-modal interactions, helping to refine the feature representation. The channel split (CSP) divides the concatenated feature map into two parts, allowing each part to undergo independent weight calculation, yielding Rweight and Dweight . These weights are then multiplied by the original input to obtain Ratt and Datt, where different parts exhibit distinct importance. This attention mechanism, while simple and lightweight, enables the model to achieve strong competitiveness through multi-scale attention acquisition, as demonstrated in B. Performance Comparison. Those operations can be represented as:
